<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<div class="space-y-6">
<div>
<h3>What foods go best with Zinfandel?</h3>
<p>Grilled meats, barbecue, tomato-based dishes, and spicy cuisines work exceptionally well with Zinfandel. The wine's bold fruit flavors and moderate tannins complement smoky, rich preparations while its acidity cuts through fatty dishes.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Should I serve Zinfandel with fish?</h3>
<p>Lighter, coastal-style Zinfandels work with meaty fish like salmon, tuna, or swordfish, especially when grilled or blackened. Avoid pairing powerful, high-alcohol Zinfandels with delicate fish preparations.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>How do I choose Zinfandel for spicy food?</h3>
<p>Select fruit-forward Zinfandels with moderate alcohol levels for spicy dishes. The wine's perceived sweetness helps balance heat while avoiding excessive alcohol burn. Off-dry styles work particularly well with very spicy cuisines.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What's the difference between old vine and regular Zinfandel for food pairing?</h3>
<p>Old vine Zinfandels offer more concentration and complexity, requiring richer, more flavorful dishes. Regular Zinfandels provide more versatility with everyday meals. Match wine intensity to food richness for best results.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>Can I cook with Zinfandel?</h3>
<p>Yes, Zinfandel works excellently in marinades, braising liquids, and reduction sauces. Its fruit character complements meat dishes while adding depth to stews and braises. Use the same wine you plan to serve for optimal pairing.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What temperature should I serve Zinfandel with food?</h3>
<p>Serve Zinfandel at 60-65°F, slightly below room temperature. This temperature balances the wine's alcohol warmth while maintaining its fruit character and food-pairing capabilities. Avoid serving too cold, which mutes flavors.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>How long does opened Zinfandel last for food pairing?</h3>
<p>Properly stored opened Zinfandel maintains good food-pairing quality for 2-3 days. Use a vacuum pump to remove air and refrigerate. Let the wine come to proper serving temperature before pairing with food.</p>
</div>

<div>
<h3>What cheese works with Zinfandel?</h3>
<p>Bold, aged cheeses like sharp cheddar, aged Gouda, and blue cheese complement Zinfandel's intensity. Soft cheeses with washed rinds also work well. Avoid very mild cheeses that get overwhelmed by the wine's power.</p>
